@Kaleal Davis 

Hello Kaleal, thank you for participating today. You bring up an interesting point.  All of the data factored into these models is based on what we have done so far. 

I wonder what these graphs would look like if we had put interventions into place sooner. Do you think it would change the number of days we would have to keep the interventions in place?

@Erikah Best 

Hello Erikah, thanks for joining us today.  You wonder if interventions stop would infections increase.  Well we certainly have a few projections here that forecast an answer to your questions.  Do you think there is anything else beyond social distancing that might affect the curve of the number of those infected? How about a catchy headline for these graphs?

Check back Friday for the 'reveal' of the origin of these graphs and a chance to interactively see how changes in certain variables might change the trajectory of these forecasts.

@Bradlee Bargerhuff 

Bradlee, thank you for participating today. Where in the graphs do you see the number of infected and hospitalized decrease?  It seems like that downward slope is different depending on which graph you look at.  

Or do you mean decreased numbers when comparing one graph to another? I wonder why the decreases are not uniform across all of the graphs.  What do you think?

@Blake blackhurst 

Hello Blake, thanks for participating today. Your wondering brings up one of the key data points forecast in these graphs: the level of hospital support.

I wonder, what do you think the graph of an area where the percentage of hospitalized with COVID-19 was high would look like versus an area where the percentage of hospitalized with COVID-19 was low?  Do you think social distancing would have the same mitigating properties in both places?

@John 

Hello John, thank you for participation in WGOITG today.  You mention testing and that certainly is part of the interventions taken into account in models these graphs represent.

Indeed these are forecasts based on a multitude of things. I wonder, if the United States is able to make widespread testing available, how do you think it would affect the projections in these graphs?  Would it affect the results in one graph more than another?
